    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f44e4603-825c-4466-85c8-14f357c6fd9f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 5-year-old girl brought in by her mother after 3 days of cough, runny nose, nasal congestion, sore throat, and low-grade fever. She looks tired but alert, sitting quietly on the exam table clutching a stuffed rabbit and leaning against her mother between bursts of dry cough. Her cheeks are slightly flushed, and she breathes comfortably through an intermittently stuffy nose, with a hoarse little voice that becomes more noticeable when she answers questions.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is usually energetic, playful, and social. She attends kindergarten, loves picture books, drawing animals, and building blanket forts with her older brother. She recently attended a class birthday party where several children had colds, and over the last week she has had less appetite, preferred softer foods, and gone to bed earlier than usual. She is still drinking fluids, though more slowly, and has had no vomiting or significant breathing difficulty.\n\nHer family describes a stable home routine with supportive parents and regular pediatric care. She lives in a smoke-free home and is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. Her mother reports that {patientName} commonly gets mild colds during the school year but is otherwise healthy and active, with no chronic lung disease, no baseline exercise intolerance, and no recent travel. Her symptoms have mainly affected sleep, mood, and school attendance rather than causing severe distress.\n\nOn appearance, she has mild watery eyes and clear nasal discharge with frequent sniffles. She appears mildly uncomfortable but non-toxic, with warm skin and good color. She engages appropriately with the examiner, follows simple instructions, and shows no signs of dehydration, lethargy, or acute respiratory compromise."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6cfc46a3-fd54-4c3b-bccb-9ec469d89b63",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no significant past medical history and has had normal growth and development. She has not required prior hospitalization and has no history of asthma, recurrent pneumonia, congenital heart disease, or immunodeficiency. Her mother reports occasional uncomplicated viral colds since starting school, all managed at home.\n\nShe takes no daily medications. Family reports adequate oral intake with slightly decreased appetite since symptom onset, but urine output remains normal. There is no known exposure to tobacco smoke at home. Several classmates recently had cough and runny nose symptoms, making a viral community exposure likely.\n\nBirth history was unremarkable, and developmental milestones were achieved on time. A remote tonsillectomy was performed for recurrent tonsillitis. There is no history of medication intolerance with antipyretics. Overall, {patientName} is a healthy child presenting with an uncomplicated acute viral upper respiratory syndrome."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
